      "sources": [
        {
          "text": "TechCrunch - YouTube clarifies policies around AI slop and upsetting videos",
          "url": "https://techcrunch.com/2026/07/20/youtube-clarifies-policies-around-ai-slop-and-upsetting-videos/"
        },
        {
          "text": "The Verge - Here are the 30,000 songs Sony is suing Udio's AI music generator over",
          "url": "https://www.theverge.com/tech/968375/sony-udio-lawsuit-songs-ai-copyright"
        },
        {
          "text": "TechCrunch - Anthropic's landmark $1.5B copyright settlement is approved",
          "url": "https://techcrunch.com/2026/07/20/anthropics-landmark-1-5b-copyright-settlement-is-approved/"
        }
      ],
      "body_html": "      <p>AI内容创作者的好日子，可能要到头了。</p>\n      <p>两条几乎同时出来的新闻，指向同一个方向。第一条：YouTube更新了变现政策，<strong>明确了哪些AI生成的低质量内容（AI slop）不能赚广告费</strong>——用AI批量生成的、没有实质内容的、纯粹为了蹭流量的视频，不能再通过YouTube Partner Program赚钱了。第二条：Sony Music Entertainment对AI音乐工具Udio提起诉讼，指控它侵犯了超过<strong>3万首</strong>歌曲的版权，从猫王的《Hound Dog》到Beyoncé的《Say My Name》再到Harry Styles的《As It Was》，跨度长达几十年。</p>\n      <p>一边是平台在清理垃圾内容，一边是版权方在追讨版权费。AI内容创作的野蛮生长期，正在以肉眼可见的速度结束。</p>\n\n      <h2>YouTube为什么开始管AI垃圾</h2>\n      <p>YouTube的AI slop政策其实不是新东西，但这次的更新更具体、更有操作性了。</p>\n      <p>以前的政策比较模糊——"我们不鼓励低质量内容"，但什么算低质量、怎么判定、会有什么后果，都说不清楚。这次更新明确了：如果你用AI批量生成视频，内容没有实质性的原创价值，只是为了蹭关键词、蹭流量、赚广告费，那你的频道会被取消变现资格，严重的还会被封号。</p>\n      <p>YouTube为什么要管？因为AI垃圾内容正在威胁它的核心资产——<strong>用户体验和广告主信任</strong>。打开YouTube搜索一个问题，结果前10条全是AI生成的水文，用户下次就去别的地方搜了；广告主发现自己的广告被投在AI垃圾视频前面，品牌形象受损，广告费也会往别处走。YouTube的商业模式建立在"高质量内容吸引用户、用户吸引广告主"的飞轮上，AI垃圾内容就是飞轮里的沙子。</p>\n      <p>这个政策对真正用AI做创意的创作者影响不大——你用AI辅助创作、但内容有自己的观点和价值，那没问题。真正受影响的是那些批量生产AI垃圾的"内容农场"——他们用AI一天生成几百条视频，铺满各种长尾关键词，靠广告矩阵赚钱。这种模式以前是灰色地带，现在明确是违规的。</p>\n\n      <h2>Sony为什么盯上Udio</h2>\n      <p>Sony起诉Udio也不是孤立事件，它是整个AI版权大战的又一个战场。</p>\n      <p>3万首歌是什么概念？Sony旗下的音乐版权可以说是全球最全的之一，从经典老歌到最新流行曲都有。它选了3万首作为起诉的代表——不是只侵犯了3万首，而是选3万首作为样本，实际上被训练的可能是几十万甚至上百万首。如果法院认定侵权成立，赔偿金可能是天文数字。</p>\n      <p>Sony的策略很清楚：<strong>先打最出头的那个，杀鸡儆猴</strong>。Udio和Suno是当前最火的两个AI音乐生成工具，用户量大、知名度高，先告其中一个，打赢了再收拾其他的。这和当年唱片公司先打Napster、再打整个P2P行业是一个路数。</p>\n      <p>但这次和当年的Napster不太一样的地方在于：AI音乐工具的法律地位还没有明确。Anthropic的版权案虽然确立了"训练可能是合理使用"的倾向，但那是文本，而且是在第九巡回法院。音乐有其特殊性——旋律、节奏、歌词，版权保护的维度更多。AI生成的音乐和原作"听起来像"算不算侵权？这个问题法官们还在摸索。</p>\n      <div class=\"pull-quote\">\"AI内容领域正在形成一个'双重收紧'的格局：平台端收紧质量，版权端收紧授权。中间还能活下来的，才是真正有创造力的内容。\"<span class=\"pull-quote__attr\">—— Dawn Vision编辑部</span></div>\n      <p>把YouTube的政策和Sony的诉讼放在一起看，一个清晰的趋势浮现出来：<strong>AI内容产业正在从"比谁多"转向"比谁好"</strong>。</p>\n      <p>过去一年，AI内容的叙事是"生产效率提升100倍""一个人就是一个团队"，好像内容越多越好。但现在平台开始做质量管控，版权方开始收费——数量的红利吃完了，接下来拼的是质量、是创意、是差异化。</p>\n      <p>对于真正的创作者来说，这其实是好消息。AI降低了创作门槛，但也让平庸变得廉价。当垃圾内容被清理掉、当版权成本内化之后，真正有想法、有风格、有深度的内容反而会更值钱。AI不会取代好的创作者——它只会让好的创作者如虎添翼，让平庸的创作者无处遁形。</p>\n      <p>明天见。</p>",
      "body_html_en": "      <p>The good old days for AI content creators might be coming to an end.</p>\n      <p>Two pieces of news that dropped almost simultaneously point in the same direction. First: YouTube updated its monetization policies, <strong>clarifying which AI-generated low-quality content (AI slop) can't earn ad revenue</strong> — videos mass-produced with AI that have no substantive content, created purely to game traffic, can no longer make money through the YouTube Partner Program. Second: Sony Music Entertainment filed a lawsuit against AI music tool Udio, alleging it infringed the copyright of over <strong>30,000</strong> songs — from Elvis Presley's \"Hound Dog\" to Beyoncé's \"Say My Name\" to Harry Styles' \"As It Was,\" spanning decades.</p>\n      <p>Platforms cleaning up garbage content on one side, copyright holders collecting royalties on the other. The wild growth era of AI content creation is ending at a pace visible to the naked eye.</p>\n\n      <h2>Why YouTube Is Cracking Down on AI Slop</h2>\n      <p>YouTube's AI slop policy isn't exactly new, but this update is more specific and more actionable.</p>\n      <p>Previous policies were vague — \"we don't encourage low-quality content\" — but what counts as low quality, how it's determined, what the consequences are, all remained unclear. This update spells it out: if you use AI to mass-produce videos with no substantive original value, just gaming keywords and traffic to earn ad revenue, your channel will lose monetization eligibility, and in severe cases get terminated.</p>\n      <p>Why does YouTube care? Because AI slop is threatening its core assets: <strong>user experience and advertiser trust.</strong> Open YouTube, search for a question, and if the top 10 results are all AI-generated fluff, users will search elsewhere next time. Advertisers finding their ads running in front of AI garbage videos will see brand damage and move their budgets elsewhere. YouTube's business model is built on the flywheel of \"high-quality content attracts users, users attract advertisers\" — AI slop is sand in the gears.</p>\n      <p>This policy won't much affect creators who genuinely use AI for creativity — if you use AI as a tool but your content has your own perspective and value, you're fine. The ones really affected are the \"content farms\" churning out AI garbage in bulk — the ones generating hundreds of videos a day with AI, flooding long-tail keywords, making money through ad networks. That model used to be a gray area. Now it's explicitly against the rules.</p>\n\n      <h2>Why Sony Has Udio in Its Sights</h2>\n      <p>Sony suing Udio also isn't an isolated incident. It's another battlefield in the broader AI copyright war.</p>\n      <p>What does 30,000 songs mean? Sony's music catalog is one of the most comprehensive in the world, spanning classic oldies to the latest hits. It chose 30,000 as representative works for the suit — not that only 30,000 were infringed, but that 30,000 were chosen as samples. The actual number used in training could be hundreds of thousands or even millions. If the court finds infringement, damages could be astronomical.</p>\n      <p>Sony's strategy is clear: <strong>hit the most prominent one first, kill the chicken to scare the monkeys.</strong> Udio and Suno are currently the two hottest AI music generation tools, with large user bases and high visibility. Sue one first, win, then go after the rest. It's the same playbook record labels used back in the day — hit Napster first, then take on the whole P2P industry.</p>\n      <p>But unlike the Napster era, the legal status of AI music tools isn't settled yet. The Anthropic copyright case, while establishing a trend toward \"training might be fair use,\" was about text and in the Ninth Circuit. Music has its特殊性 — melody, rhythm, lyrics — more dimensions of copyright protection. Does an AI-generated song that \"sounds similar\" to an original count as infringement? Judges are still figuring that out.</p>\n      <div class=\"pull-quote\">&quot;The AI content space is forming a 'dual tightening' pattern: platforms tightening quality on one end, copyright holders tightening licensing on the other. What survives in the middle is content with real creativity.&quot;<span class=\"pull-quote__attr\">— The Dawn Vision Editorial Desk</span></div>\n      <p>Putting YouTube's policy and Sony's lawsuit together, a clear trend emerges: <strong>the AI content industry is shifting from 'more is better' to 'better is better.'</strong></p>\n      <p>Over the past year, the narrative around AI content was \"100x productivity gains,\" \"one person is a whole team\" — as if more content was always better content. But now platforms are doing quality control, and copyright holders are collecting fees. The quantity dividend is eaten up. Next comes competition on quality, creativity, differentiation.</p>\n      <p>For real creators, this is actually good news. AI lowered the barriers to creation, but it also made mediocrity cheap. When garbage content gets cleaned up and copyright costs get internalized, content with real ideas, style, and depth will actually be worth more. AI won't replace good creators — it will make good creators even more powerful, and make mediocre creators nowhere to hide.</p>\n      <p>See you tomorrow.</p>",
